---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const reviewed = "July 2026";
---
<Base
  title="Company Formation & Tax in Singapore 2026: 17% Corporate Tax & 9% GST | ARM Management"
  description="A current guide to setting up a company in Singapore — the flat 17% corporate tax, partial and start-up exemptions, 9% GST, one-tier dividends and no capital gains tax, with official sources."
>
  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <div class="page-hero__bg" style="background-image:url('/images/ed-shenzhen.jpg')"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__overlay"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__content container">
        <span class="eyebrow">Guide · Singapore</span>
        <h1>Company Formation &amp; Tax in Singapore</h1>
        <p>Asia's benchmark holding and headquarters jurisdiction — a flat 17% corporate tax softened by generous exemptions, no capital gains tax, and tax-free dividends.</p>
        <div class="btn-row" style="justify-content:flex-start;margin-top:30px">
          <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Speak With a Senior Advisor →</a>
          <a href="/services/company-formation" class="btn-secondary">Company Formation Services</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section--warm">
      <div class="container--narrow">
        <div class="guide-meta reveal">
          <span><strong>Last reviewed:</strong> {reviewed}</span>
          <span><strong>Primary source:</strong>
            <a href="https://www.iras.gov.sg" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore (IRAS)</a>
          </span>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <p class="reveal lede">Singapore combines a flat 17% corporate tax with tiered exemptions that pull the effective rate on early profits far lower, a one-tier dividend system in which distributions reach shareholders tax-free, and no tax on capital gains. Add same-day incorporation, an unrivalled treaty network and its role as the region's financial centre, and it remains the default base for Asian holding structures and regional headquarters.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">The headline numbers</h2>
          <div class="rate-table reveal">
            <table>
              <thead><tr><th>Tax</th><th>Rate</th></tr></thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Corporate income tax (flat)</td><td>17%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Effective rate on early profits (after exemptions)</td><td>~4–8%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>GST (standard)</td><td>9%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Capital gains tax</td><td>None</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Dividend tax (one-tier system)</td><td>0%</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="reveal">GST registration becomes mandatory once taxable turnover exceeds <strong>S$1 million</strong> over 12 months; exports of goods and international services are zero-rated. There is no withholding tax on dividends paid abroad, which is central to Singapore's appeal as a holding location.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Exemptions that shape the effective rate</h2>
          <ul class="reveal">
            <li><strong>Start-up Tax Exemption (SUTE)</strong> — for the first three years of assessment, qualifying new companies receive 75% exemption on the first S$100,000 of chargeable income and 50% on the next S$100,000.</li>
            <li><strong>Partial Tax Exemption</strong> — all other companies receive 75% exemption on the first S$10,000 and 50% on the next S$190,000 of chargeable income, every year.</li>
            <li><strong>Foreign-sourced income reliefs</strong> — qualifying foreign dividends, branch profits and service income can be exempt when remitted, subject to the "subject to tax" and headline-rate conditions.</li>
            <li><strong>Incentive regimes</strong> — concessionary rates for fund management, finance and treasury centres, maritime and headquarters activities through EDB and MAS schemes.</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="callout reveal">
            <strong>Pillar Two now applies to large groups.</strong> From 2025, multinational groups with global revenue above €750 million face a 15% minimum effective rate in Singapore through a domestic top-up tax. For founders, SMEs and mid-market holding structures below that threshold, the classic 17%-with-exemptions arithmetic is unchanged.
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Forming the company</h2>
          <p class="reveal">The standard vehicle is the <strong>private limited company (Pte. Ltd.)</strong>, registered with ACRA through BizFile — often completed within a day. Requirements are light: minimum paid-up capital of S$1, at least one shareholder (100% foreign ownership permitted), and at least <strong>one director ordinarily resident in Singapore</strong> — typically satisfied through a nominee or local appointment if the founders are abroad. A company secretary must be appointed within six months, and a registered local address is required. Annual filings comprise the ACRA annual return and the corporate tax return (ECI and Form C-S/C).</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Frequently asked questions</h2>
          <div class="reveal">
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is Singapore's corporate tax rate in 2026?</h4><p>A flat 17%. Start-up and partial exemptions reduce the effective rate on the first S$200,000 of profits to roughly 4–8% for qualifying companies.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>Does Singapore tax capital gains or dividends?</h4><p>No. There is no capital gains tax, and under the one-tier system dividends paid from taxed profits are tax-free for shareholders, with no dividend withholding tax.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is the GST rate in Singapore?</h4><p>9%, with mandatory registration above S$1 million of annual taxable turnover. Exports and international services are zero-rated.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>Can a foreigner own a Singapore company fully?</h4><p>Yes — 100% foreign ownership is permitted. The company needs at least one Singapore-resident director, which can be arranged locally without giving up ownership or control.</p></div>
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Official sources</h2>
          <ul class="sources reveal">
            <li><a href="https://www.iras.gov.sg" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IRAS</a> — corporate tax and GST</li>
            <li><a href="https://www.acra.gov.sg" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ACRA</a> — company registration</li>
            <li><a href="https://www.edb.gov.sg" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Singapore Economic Development Board</a></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="reveal disclaimer">This guide is general information prepared by ARM Management and is current as at {reviewed}. It is not legal or tax advice; exemption and incentive eligibility carries conditions and rules change. Confirm against IRAS, or with an advisor, before acting.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="cta-section guide-cta">
      <span class="eyebrow is-center reveal" style="justify-content:center">Speak With ARM</span>
      <h2 class="reveal">Structure a Singapore company the right way.</h2>
      <p class="reveal">ARM Management advises founders, investors and holding structures on Singapore incorporation, tax-exemption eligibility and cross-border structuring across Asia. Begin with a confidential conversation.</p>
      <div class="btn-row reveal">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Schedule a Consultation →</a>
        <a href="/services/company-formation" class="btn-secondary">Company Formation Services</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

